## Planning
# Following review of background literature, fisheries information, PSCIS and `bcfishpass` outputs, both modelled and PSCIS sites were selected for follow up with Phase 1 and 2 assessments. Results are included as a zipped package of Google Earth kml files stored  [here](https://github.com/NewGraphEnvironment/fish_passage_skeena_2021_reporting/raw/master/data/planning_kmls/elk_planning_kmls.zip).


5.1 Phase 1

Field assessments were conducted between August 09 2021 and September 16 2021 by Allan Irvine, R.P.Bio. and Kyle Prince, P.Biol., Tieasha Pierre, Vern Joseph, Dallas Nikal, Alexandria Nikal, Chad Lewis, Tim Wilson, Adam Wrench, Lars Reese-Hanson and Don Morgan. A total of 191 Phase 1 assessments were conducted with 77 crossings considered “passable,” 10 crossings considered “potential” barriers and 84 crossings considered “barriers” according to threshold values based on culvert embedment, outlet drop, slope, diameter (relative to channel size) and length (MoE 2011). Georeferenced field maps are presented in here and available for bulk download as Attachment 1. A summary of crossings assessed, a cost benefit analysis and priority ranking for follow up for Phase 1 sites presented in Table 5.1. Detailed data with photos are presented in Appendix - Phase 1 Fish Passage Assessment Data and Photos.


“Barrier” and “Potential Barrier” rankings used in this project followed MoE (2011) and reflect an assessment of passability for juvenile salmon or small resident rainbow trout at any flows potentially present throughout the year (Clarkin et al. 2005 ; Bell 1991; Thompson 2013). As noted in Bourne et al. (2011), with a detailed review of different criteria in Kemp and O’Hanley (2010), passability of barriers can be quantified in many different ways. Fish physiology (i.e. species, length, swim speeds) can make defining passability complex but with important implications for evaluating connectivity and prioritizing remediation candidates (Bourne et al. 2011; Shaw et al. 2016; Mahlum et al. 2014; Kemp and O’Hanley 2010). Washington Department of Fish & Wildlife (2009) present criteria for assigning passability scores to culverts that have already been assessed as barriers in coarser level assessments. These passability scores provide additional information to feed into decision making processes related to the prioritization of remediation site candidates and have potential for application in British Columbia.

5.2 Phase 2

During 2021 field assessments, habitat confirmation assessments were conducted at 32 sites in the Bulkley River watershed group and one site in the Morice River watershed group. A total of approximately NAkm of stream was assessed, fish sampling utilizing electrofishing was conducted at five sites, and five sites were mapped using remotely piloted aircraft. Georeferenced field maps are presented in here and available for bulk download as Attachment 1.


As collaborative decision making was ongoing at the time of reporting, site prioritization can be considered preliminary. In total, Nine crossings were rated as high priorities for proceeding to design for replacement, 7 crossings were rated as moderate priorities, and 4 crossings were rated as low priorities. Results are summarized in Figure 5.1 and Tables 5.2 - ?? with raw habitat and fish sampling data included in digital format as Attachment 3. A summary of preliminary modelling results illustrating the quantity of chinook, coho and steelhead spawning and rearing habitat potentially available upstream of each crossing as estimated by measured/modelled channel width and upstream accessible stream length are presented in Figure 5.2. Detailed information for each site assessed with Phase 2 assessments (including maps) are presented within site specific appendices to this document.

123775 Witset Creek Highway 16 606445 6099726 – – Low low Wet mud substrate. Water in channel may be due to previous rainfall. No flow. Beaver activity present water level at extremely low to none. Thick brush on both. Stream channel overgrown, possible dewatering. At Witset lake outlet access is private land. At waypoint WP020 lake outflow disconnected from stream. witset mainenance actively traps beavers to prevent flood events as of 2017. Waypoint WP021 water levels appeared to have dropped 60cm, dock dropped and is no longer floating. Water receded 2.1m at start of summer.
124420 Mission Creek Highway 16 586632 6122395 – – Medium – ~150m higher gradient ~3-4% with cobble dominant then levelling out. Frequent pockets of gravels suitable for spawning throughout. High value spawning habitat in upper end of survey area. Refer to Natalie’s report.
124421 Tributary to Waterfall Creek 11th Ave 589467 6123042 – – Medium – Not sure about crossing number (furthest south crossing). High to moderate habitat. Slow moving almost wetland like stream. Deep glides throughout. Lots of instream vegetation, overhanging vegetation, and undercut banks. Initially deep organic / fines substrate. Near top of survey, gradient increased slightly and substrate goes to small gravel. Moderate to high stagnant water often smelling of sulfur. Tons of vegetation, shrubs and sedge on banks. Water almost at bankful. Appears to have very unstable flows.
124422 Tributary to Waterfall Creek Highway 16 589500 6123162 – – Medium – Must be a beaver dam arount waypoint WP426. Could not find it

197379 Tributary to Owen Creek Morice-Owen FSR 640961 6005930 – – High – Initiall steep below falls, cascading with pools. Bedrock dominated substrate. Further downstream gratient is ~ 4. Lots of undercut banks with some pools. Healthy riparian vegetation providing cover. Functional debris habitat. Overall very nice stream, good flows, plentiful habitat. Large woody debris jam was big but had water running under.

197960 Corya Creek Railway 605786 6099884 – – High high Channel and wetted width taken using rangefinder. 3 measurements for each to esure accuracy.
197962 Peacock Creek Morice FSR 643460 6025890 – – Medium high Large woody debris feature (0.9m) was across entire wetted width. Very functional but may be challenging in low water for upstream access. Great stream complex with all types of habitat throughout and consistent. Tough choise fro dominant however, boulders with straight runs of short riffles occur consistently on survey area. There are also consistent undercut banks, large and small woody debris and some nice pools. A few fish encountered on survey. Signs of high powerful flows, including clumped large woody debris, still functional but can be piled up in a few areas. Large channel and several side channels. One side channel area has large woody debris pile at the top end and main flow appears recently diverted into pile and over newer area. Gradient stays consistent with a few riffles / small cascades around 5. Selected decoupled however, some areas had steep sided banks and landscape. Algae present but not often and not in huge quantities.
197967 Taman Creek Highway 16 692435 6032331 – – Medium moderate First ~250m is beaver influenced area with dry channel. Frequent pockets of gravels and small cobbles suitable for rainbow trout and coho salmon spawning. Medium value habitat. Canyon section has deep bedrock pools with small fish present and no large woody debris. One deep pool upstream of canyon section contained likely 2-3 year old juveniles (coloring indicated rainbow trout, unverified).
197975 Ailport Creek Private Driveway 680832 6040045 – – Medium high Moderate / high value habitat, lots of anthropogenic damage in first section of survey. Several dredges first 80m removed all habitat. Also grazed heavily initially so no vegetation on left bank. Heavy grazing continuous for another few hundred meters. Large woody debris somewhat rare on bottom half, signs of removal and often not across stream. Deep pools, undercut banks, and overhanging vegetation occurs in areas and holds most value for fish. Also instream boulders (small ones) and large cobbles provide cover. Fence across stream halfway up. Some areas have large piles of substrate deposited within extent of channel (perhaps from flooding). Saw some fish but not as consistently as other sites. Sometimes only water flowing through middle, no cover or habitat for stretches at a time. Need grazing management and stop dredging.
197976 Ailport Creek Highway 16 680645 6039756 – – High moderate Nice stream, moderate habitat value, fish sighted throughout. Deep pools are dominant but not nearly as good compared to below highway. Some nice undercut banks thoughout with overhanging vegetation and small woody debris near or over them. Sloped banks common throughout. Extensive algae growth seen during entire survey. Large woody debris quite rare and not seen mush embedded or across channel. Fences accrosss creek near highway including electric fence. Riparian / bank damage from livestock quite minimal and only seen in a few places as trails, perhaps watering sites.
198000 McBride Creek Nanika FSR 605511 5992667 – – High moderate High quality habitat lots of instream vegetation including vascular plants. Chanel quite large with grass and sedge on shoulders. Huge large woody debris pile at outflow of McBride Lake (looks like only log boom structure)
198008 Tributary to Nanika River Spur 606426 5986782 – – Medium low Multiple channels. May have surveyed non-dominant channel (likely). Bottom 100m is low gradient gravels with good slow for time of year. Dolly Varden known upstream channel cannont confirm habitat upstream of 100m but likely close to mapped gradients with no lakes upstream indicating stream is passable to Dolly Varden.

## Fish Sampling

# Fish sampling was conducted at five sites with a total of `r tab_fish_summary %>% filter(species_code == 'WCT') %>% pull(count_fish) %>% sum()` westslope cutthout trout,  `r tab_fish_summary %>% filter(species_code == 'EB') %>% pull(count_fish) %>% sum()` eastern brook trout and `r tab_fish_summary %>% filter(species_code == 'BT') %>% pull(count_fish) %>% sum()` bull trout captured.  Westslope cutthrout trout were captured at three of the sites sampled with fork length data delineated into life stages: fry (&le;60mm), parr (>60 to 110mm), juvenile (>110mm to 140mm) and adult (>140mm) by visually assessing the histogram presented in Figure \@ref(fig:fish-histogram).  Fish sampling results are presented in detail within individual habitat confirmation site memos within the appendices of this document with westslope cutthrout trout density results also presented in Figure \@ref(fig:plot-fish-all).  
knitr::include_graphics("fig/fish_histogram.png")


plot_fish_box_all2 <- function(dat = hab_fish_dens){#, sp = 'RB'
  dat %>%
    filter(
      species_code  != 'MW'
      # &
      #   species_code == species
    ) %>%
    ggplot(., aes(x = location, y =density_100m2)) +
    geom_boxplot()+
    facet_grid(site ~ species_code, scales ="fixed", #life_stage
               as.table = T)+
    # theme_bw()+
    theme(legend.position = "none", axis.title.x=element_blank()) +
    geom_dotplot(binaxis='y', stackdir='center', dotsize=1)+
    ylab(expression(Density ~ (Fish/100 ~  m^2))) +
    ggdark::dark_theme_bw()
}


plot_fish_box_all2()


bcfp_xref_plot <- xref_bcfishpass_names %>% 
  filter(!is.na(id_join) &
           bcfishpass %ilike% 'below' &
           !bcfishpass %ilike% 'all' &
           (bcfishpass %ilike% 'rearing' | 
              bcfishpass %ilike% 'spawning')) 

bcfishpass_phase2_plot_prep <- bcfishpass %>% 
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), round, 1)) %>%
    filter(stream_crossing_id %in% (pscis_phase2 %>% pull(pscis_crossing_id))) %>% 
  select(stream_crossing_id, all_of(bcfp_xref_plot$bcfishpass)) %>% 
  # filter(stream_crossing_id != 197665) %>% 
  mutate(stream_crossing_id = as.factor(stream_crossing_id)) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = ch_spawning_belowupstrbarriers_km:st_rearing_belowupstrbarriers_km)  %>% 
  filter(value > 0.0 &
           !is.na(value)
         , !name %ilike% 'sk'
         ) %>% 
  mutate(name = stringr::str_replace_all(name, '_belowupstrbarriers_km', ''),
         name = stringr::str_replace_all(name, '_rearing', ' rearing'),
         name = stringr::str_replace_all(name, '_spawning', ' spawning'))
    # rename('Habitat type' = name,
    #        "Habitat (km)" = value)
  
  
  
 bcfishpass_phase2_plot_prep %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = stream_crossing_id, y = value)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
  facet_wrap(~name, ncol = 2)+
  ggdark::dark_theme_bw(base_size = 11)+
   theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90, hjust=1, vjust=0.5)) +
  labs(x = "Site", y = "Modelled habitat (km)")
